{{For|information about other uses of the word ''Ark''|Ark (disambiguation){{!}}Ark}} {{EngvarB|date=October 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image = Maryland Tri Cen 1934 Issue-3c.jpg | Ship image size = 200px | Ship caption = ''"Ark"'' and the ''"Dove"'', shown here in a 1934 U.S. commemorative postage stamp. }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header = | Ship country = [[Kingdom of England]] | Ship flag = {{flag|England}} | Ship name = ''Ark'' | Ship owner = Hired by [[Cecilius Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore|Cecilius Calvert, second Baron or Lord Baltimore]], (1605-1675) | Ship ordered = | Ship builder = | Ship original cost = | Ship laid down = | Ship launched = c. 1630 | Ship acquired = | Ship commissioned = | Ship decommissioned = | Ship in service = | Ship out of service = | Ship renamed = | Ship struck = | Ship reinstated = | Ship honors = | Ship captured = | Ship fate = | Ship status = | Ship notes = }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header = | Header caption = | Ship class = | Ship tons burthen = 400 | Ship length = Approximately {{convert|132|ft}} on deck<ref>Ship characteristics derived from plans drawn using 17th Century techniques.</ref> | Ship beam = {{convert|32|ft}} | Ship draft = {{convert|14|-|15|ft}} | Ship hold depth = {{convert|14|ft}} | Ship propulsion = Sail | Ship sail plan = Three masted, Spritsail& spritsail topsail, fore course, fore topsail & fore topgallant, main course, main topsail and main topgallant, Lateen mizzen with square topsail. | Ship complement = Approximately 40 seamen | Ship armament = Unknown, but probably capable of mounting 20-25 cannon. | Ship notes = }} |}
[[File:Maryland Dove.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A modern reconstruction and replica of a small 17th Century English trading ship, the ''[[Maryland Dove]]'' at [[St. Mary's City, Maryland]] is approximately the same size as her namesake, the c. 1630 ''Dove'' which accompanied the ''Ark'' on the historic trans-oceanic voyage in late 1633 and early 1634.]] '''''Ark''''' was a 400-ton [[Kingdom of England|English]] merchant ship hired by [[Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore]] (1605–1675), to bring roughly 140 English colonists and their equipment and supplies to the new colony and [[Province of Maryland]], one of the [[Original 13 states|original thirteen colonies]] of [[British North America]] on the Atlantic Ocean eastern seaboard. On the historic trans-oceanic voyage from England in late 1633 and early 1634, ''Ark'' was accompanied by the smaller 40-ton [[pinnace (ship's boat)|pinnace]] ''[[Maryland Dove|Dove]]''.{{fact|date=July 2018}}
==Maryland expedition== On {{start date and age|1633|11|22|df=y|paren=y}}, after several delays, the two ships, ''Ark'' and ''Dove'', sailed from the [[Isle of Wight]] off the south coast of England. Three days later a storm in the [[English Channel]] separated ''Ark'' from ''Dove''. When ''Dove'' disappeared from view, she was flying distress lanterns, and those aboard ''Ark'' assumed she had sunk in the storm. A second more violent storm hit ''Ark'' on 29 November 1633 and lasted three days, finally subsiding on 1 December. In the midst of the storm the mainsail was split in half and the crew was forced to tie down the tiller and whipstaff so the ship [[Lying ahull|lay ahull]]', keeping her bow to the wind and waves as she drifted. This was the last bad weather ''Ark'' encountered on the trans-Atlantic voyage.{{fact|date=July 2018}}
On 25 December 1633, wine was passed out to celebrate [[Christmas]]. The following day, 30 colonists fell ill with a fever brought on by excessive drinking and 12 died, including two of the Roman Catholic colonists. These were the only losses suffered on the voyage. On 3 January 1633/34 (see below on the start of the new year), ''Ark'' arrived at the island of [[Barbados]] in the West Indies after a voyage of 42 days from England. About two weeks later, ''Dove'' arrived. As it later developed, ''Dove'' had been able to reach the shelter of [[Plymouth, England|Plymouth]] harbour where she rode out the storm.{{fact|date=July 2018}}
On 24 January 1633/34, the ships departed [[Barbados]]. An earlier departure was intended, but was delayed because [[Richard Orchard]], master (captain) the ''Dove'' had departed inland to collect some debts and could not be found on the intended sailing date. After making a few other stops in the [[Caribbean Sea]], on 24 February 1633/34, the ships arrived at [[Point Comfort]] (now called Old Point Comfort) at the mouths of the [[James River (Virginia)|James]], [[Nansemond River|Nansemond]], and [[Elizabeth River (Virginia)|Elizabeth]] rivers, which formed the great harbor of [[Hampton Roads]] in Virginia. This ended their ocean voyage which had lasted slightly over three months, of which 66 days were actually spent at sea. The two ships briefly stopped in [[Jamestown, Virginia]] up the [[James River (Virginia)|James River]].{{fact|date=July 2018}}
After a week's stay, the Calvert colonists then sailed northward up the large expanse of the Bay, landing on [[St. Clement's Island State Park|St. Clement's Island]], also known as Blakistone Island, on the north shore of the [[Potomac River]], across from Virginia's northern border, on 25 March 1634. This day was thereafter celebrated annually in the colony and free State as "[[Maryland Day]]". The colonists planted a large cross, claiming the land in the name of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]), King of England, and holding their first communal [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] led by the accompanying [[Jesuit]] chaplain, Father [[Andrew White (Jesuit)|Andrew White]]. The day "25 March" has been traditionally taken to mark the end of the voyage, although, in fact, the voyage had actually ended earlier on 24 February, when the ''Ark'' and the ''Dove'' arrived at Point Comfort entering the North American continental waters. 25 March is the Feast of the Annunciation of the Blessed Virgin Mary, a major festival day in the liturgical calendar. Until 1752, when England finally adopted the [[Gregorian Calendar]] as opposed to the older, now inaccurate [[Julian Calendar]], 25 March was the start of the civil new year,<ref>[[Old Style and New Style dates|"old Style" and "New Style" dates]]</ref> hence the practice of writing dates from 1 January to 25 March as 1633/34.<ref>The chronology given here is derived from Father [[Andrew White (Jesuit)|Andrew White's]] diary account of the voyage using the Barbara Lawatsch-Boomgaarden's translation: White, Father Andrew, Lawatsch-Boomgaarden Barbara, trans. ''"Voyage to Maryland"'', Wauconda, Bolchazy-Carducci Publishers, 1995.</ref>
Although too small for the intended settlement, St. Clement's provided a relatively secure base from which [[Leonard Calvert]], (1606-1647), new first [[Governor of Maryland]] and younger brother of Cecilius, could explore the area and negotiate the purchase of land for the new colony. After a brief three-week stay on the island, the new Marylanders occupied a nearby [[Piscataway tribe|Piscataway]] Indian village they had purchased on the St. George's (later the [[St. Mary's River (Maryland)|St. Mary's]]) River, several miles (kilometers) southeast from St. Clement's and about {{convert|12|mi}} northwest from [[Point Lookout, Maryland|Point Lookout]], where the Potomac River enters the Chesapeake Bay. The new English settlement was named "[[St. Mary's City, Maryland|St. Mary's City]]" in honor of The Virgin, which later became the provincial capital, and later the county seat/courthouse in the first county to be "erected" (established), [[St. Mary's County, Maryland|St. Mary's County]].{{fact|date=July 2018}}
In the early summer of 1634, the ''Ark'' returned to England. The ''Dove'', which had been also purchased by Calvert and the gentry investors in the new colony, remained for the settlers' use in and around the Bay and coasts of Maryland.{{fact|date=July 2018}}
In August 1635, the ''Dove'' sailed for England carrying timber and beaver pelts, but she never arrived home and was presumed lost in a storm. ''[[Maryland Dove]]'' is a modern replica of the vessel.{{fact|date=July 2018}}
===Passengers=== Among the passengers on board the ''Ark'' and the ''Dove'' were Leonard Calvert and [[Thomas Greene (governor)|Thomas Greene]], (1610-1651), of [[Bobbing, Kent]], the first two [[Governor of Maryland|governors]] of Maryland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msa.md.gov/megafile/msa/speccol/sc3500/sc3520/000100/000198/html/198bio.html |title=Leonard Calvert ''MSA SC 3520-198'' |publisher=Maryland State Archives |date=2003-03-07}}</ref> Leonard Calvert was the second son of [[George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore]], the first proprietor of the Province of Maryland. His elder brother Cecilius, who inherited the colony and the title, appointed Leonard governor in his absence.<ref name=sparky>{{cite book |last=Sparks |first=Jared |title=The Library of American Biography: George Calvert, the first Lord Baltimore |publisher=Charles C. Little and James Brown |year=1846 |location=Boston |pages=16- |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RBsNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR3&dq=Leonard+Calvert#PPA16,M1 |isbn=}}</ref>
